<HEADLINE>
<P>
KING COACH COULD RETURN IN 3 WEEKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE SPRINGER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
King Coach Tom Webster underwent successful inner-ear surgery Tuesday at St. 
Vincent's Hospital in Los Angeles and could be back with the team in less than 
three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. James Sheehy discovered a leak of inner-ear fluid, an injury similar to one 
Webster suffered several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
The new injury was caused when Webster, 40, fell while showering in his 
Edmonton hotel room Jan. 26. 
</P>
<P>
Webster was forced to resign as coach of the New York Rangers in January of 
1987 when the original inner-ear problem prevented him from flying. Surgery 
repaired that injury. 
</P>
<P>
Webster's condition was originally diagnosed as a concussion, but dizziness 
continued. Sheehy found the new injury in the same area as the old. 
</P>
</TEXT>
