<HEADLINE>
<P>
TYSON'S SISTER DIES OF APPARENT HEART ATTACK AT 24 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 24-year-old sister of deposed heavyweight champion Mike Tyson died of an 
apparent heart attack today, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Denise Anderson was found unconscious by her husband in their home in Queens. 
</P>
<P>
Initial reports indicated that Anderson, who weighed between 300 and 400 
pounds, may have died of cardiac arrest. 
</P>
<P>
Tyson, 23, lost his undisputed world heavyweight title Feb. 11 when he was 
knocked out in the 10th round by James (Buster) Douglas in Tokyo, in one of 
boxing's greatest upsets. 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Don King, Tyson's promoter, said the fighter was "very, very 
dejected" after hearing the news. 
</P>
<P>
In "Fire and Fear," a book about Tyson, author Jose Torres quoted the fighter 
as saying: "You know something? I never read a book or played school when I was 
a child. I didn't relate to that. I remember being close to my sister, Denise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
